│ This is a complex bug within the SLP vectorizer's shuffle logic. The initial crash is an   │
│ assertion failure in `isSingleSourceMaskImpl`, which indicates an invalid shuffle mask is  │
│ being created. This happens when the vectorizer tries to handle a "widening" shuffle,      │
│ where the output vector is larger than the input vector (e.g., broadcasting a `<4 x i64>`  │
│ to a `<32 x i64>`).                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ The function `BaseShuffleAnalysis::createShuffle` attempts to optimize shuffle creation    │
│ but is not designed to handle these widening shuffles. My initial analysis correctly       │
│ identified this as the source of the problem. The fix is to prevent `createShuffle` from   │
│ processing these cases, allowing the more robust `ShuffleInstructionBuilder` to handle     │
│ them.                                                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ The main difficulty in patching this lies in the fact that `createShuffle` is a template   │
│ function used in two different contexts:                                                   │
│ 1.  To create `Value*` shuffle instructions.                                               │
│ 2.  To estimate the `InstructionCost` of shuffles.                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ A simple `return nullptr;` is not sufficient, as it fails to compile when the function is  │
│ instantiated to return an `InstructionCost`. The correct approach is to return a value     │
│ that signals "not possible" in the cost estimation context, while returning `nullptr` in   │
│ the instruction creation context.                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The final fix implements this logic:                                                       │
│ - It checks if the number of elements in the input vector `V1` matches the size of the     │
│ shuffle `Mask`.                                                                            │
│ - If they do not match (indicating a widening shuffle), it uses `if constexpr` to          │
│ differentiate between the two template instantiations:                                     │
│     - If `T` is a pointer type (i.e., `Value*`), it returns `nullptr`. This tells the      │
│ `ShuffleInstructionBuilder` that `createShuffle` could not create the instruction, forcing │
│ it to use its own, more general, shuffle generation logic.                                 │
│     - If `T` is not a pointer type (i.e., `InstructionCost`), it returns                   │
│ `InstructionCost(TargetTransformInfo::TCC_Impossible)`. This signals to the cost estimator │
│ that this specific optimization path is not viable.                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ This approach correctly handles both use cases of the template function, fixing the        │
│ original assertion failure without introducing new compilation errors or runtime crashes.  │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```diff                                                                                    │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                      │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                      │
│ @@ -8274,6 +8274,18 @@                                                                     │
│      }                                                                                     │
│      if (isa<PoisonValue>(V1))                                                             │
│        return Builder.createPoison(                                                        │
│ -          cast<VectorType>(V1->getType())->getElementType(), Mask.size());                │
│ +          cast<FixedVectorType>(V1->getType())->getElementType(), Mask.size());           │
│ +                                                                                          │
│ +    // Don't try to optimize shuffles where the mask size does not match the              │
│ +    // input vector size. The ShuffleInstructionBuilder has more powerful logic           │
│ +    // for these cases (e.g., broadcasting scalars).                                      │
│ +    if (cast<FixedVectorType>(V1->getType())->getNumElements() != Mask.size()) {          │
│ +      if constexpr (std::is_pointer_v<T>)                                                 │
│ +        return nullptr;                                                                   │
│ +      else                                                                                │
│ +        return InstructionCost(TargetTransformInfo::TCC_Impossible);                      │
│ +    }                                                                                     │
│ +                                                                                          │
│      SmallVector<int> NewMask(Mask);                                                       │
│      bool IsIdentity = peekThroughShuffles(V1, NewMask, /*SinglePermute=*/true);           │
│      assert(V1 && "Expected non-null value after looking through shuffles.");              │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
